On New Year's Day 2012, British radio station [[BBC Radio 6 Music]], solely broadcast music on the vinyl format, with records coming from the collections of presenters and DJs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/dec/26/bbc-6-music-vinyl-new-years-day|title=BBC Radio 6 Music goes vinyl-only on New Year's Day|date=26 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 November 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref>

==Record Store Day==
{{main|Record Store Day}}

Record Store Day is an internationally celebrated day observed the third Saturday of April each year. Its purpose, as conceived by independent record store employee Chris Brown, is to celebrate the art of music.<ref name=RSD>{{cite web|url=http://recordstoreday.com/CustomPage/614|title=RECORD STORE DAY - ABOUT US|website=Recordstoreday.com|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> The day brings together fans, artists, and thousands of independent [[record store]]s across the world.<ref name=usatoday>{{Cite news| last = Passey| first = Brian| title = Vinyl records spin back into vogue| url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/retail/2011-02-25-vinyl25_ST_N.htm| accessdate = 2 March 2011| work=USA Today| date=26 February 2011}}</ref>

Record Store Day was officially founded in 2007<ref name=RSD/> and is celebrated globally<ref name=RSD/> with hundreds of recording and other artists participating in the day by making special appearances, performances, meet and greets with their fans, the holding of art exhibits, and the issuing of special [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] and CD releases along with other promotional products to mark the occasion.

In 2013, for the week of Record Store Day in the United Kingdom, 68,936 records were sold (an 86.5% rise from 36,957 in 2012). This can be broken down into 1,249 7" albums, 25,100 12" albums, 27,042 7" singles and 15,545 12" singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/record-store-day-vinyl-sales-leap-87-year-on-year/054497|title=Record Store Day vinyl sales leap 87% year-on-year - News - Music Week|website=Musicweek.com|accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>
From December 29, 2017 to June 28, 2018 there has been a 19.2% increase in vinyl sales compared to the same period of last year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Helfet |first1=Gabrielle |title=Over 7.6 million vinyl LPs were sold in the US during the first half of 2018 |url=https://thevinylfactory.com/news/record-vinyl-sales-usa-first-half-2018/ |website=the vinyl factory |accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>
Vinyl sales hold over 18% of physical record sales in the United States a 7% increase from previous years. 
<ref>{{cite web |last1=Helfet |first1=Gabrielle |title=Over 7.6 million vinyl LPs were sold in the US during the first half of 2018 |url=https://thevinylfactory.com/news/record-vinyl-sales-usa-first-half-2018/ |website=the vinyl factory |accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>

==Charts==
===UK Official Record Store Chart===
The [[Official Record Store Chart]] is a weekly [[music chart]] based on physical sales of albums in almost 100&nbsp;independent [[record store]]s in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|title=New chart for record shop sales|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/new-chart-for-record-shop-sales-7654781.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|issn=0951-9467|oclc=185201487|date=18 April 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67OATGLoP?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/new-chart-for-record-shop-sales-7654781.html|archivedate=3 May 2012|deadurl=no|accessdate=20 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17742623|title=Independent record store chart launched in the UK|date=17 April 2012|publisher=BBC News|location=London|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67OAVlG1m?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17742623|archivedate=3 May 2012|deadurl=no|accessdate=20 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is compiled by the [[Official Charts Company]] (OCC), and each week's number one is first announced on Sunday evenings on the OCC's official website.

The chart's launch was first announced by the OCC on 17 April 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-new-official-record-store-chart-is-go-1345/|title=The new Official Record Store Chart is go!|first=Laura|last=Kreisler|date=17 April 2012|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|location=London|accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>&nbsp;– at the time, British record stores were selling 4.5&nbsp;million albums per year, and were contributing towards 95&nbsp;per cent of the country's total vinyl sales.

